  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Edict Enfeoffing as Marquis of Jinyang
  author: Lee Gyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    We observe that since ancient times, when fiefs have been granted to those of different surnames, it has not followed the customary practice of the imperial clan. Rather, such honors are bestowed only upon those whose exceptional merit and weighty renown have illuminated their age. Hence such appointments remain rare even within a generation. Consider then: since the founding of our realm, how many have possessed virtue and accomplishment equal to yours? How could We alone deny you the honor of a fief and the title of marquis?

    We once issued a decree enfeoffing you, but you declined with such steadfast virtue that We suspended the matter. Yet We cannot make known our intentions to every household in the land—how can We be certain that none whisper We guard our seals too jealously? This troubles not only Our own heart, but surely weighs upon the consciences of all.

    Consider what you have done for Us: You raised Us to the throne and determined the succession, steadying Our realm when barbarian hordes ravaged the land. With prescience like divine sight, you calculated enemy movements and adapted to circumstance. You led the people in relocating our capital, thus preserving our ancestral shrines. You crushed rebellion and restored the integrity of Our court—these are the accomplishments that benefit all Three Lands. And when the Khitans under their general Salita plagued all beneath heaven, your brilliant stratagems felled him with a single arrow, bringing joy to myriad nations.

    Behold: such extraordinary and unprecedented service rendered to Us, to the Three Lands, and to all the world—history and antiquity afford no parallel. Should We fail to honor your wishes through hesitation and weak resolve, not only the Three Lands but all the world would question Our judgment. Moreover, you once declined to inherit your father's rank, displaying exemplary integrity. Only when your own merit had accumulated and satisfied all hearts did you accept—valuing virtue over hereditary privilege. Such wisdom, such careful discernment, shall flow as beautiful legend through ten thousand generations.

    Rewards cannot long be delayed, and opportunity slips away with time. Therefore, We now dispatch our emissaries bearing the imperial edict to solemnly invest you as Marquis of Jinyang, that your virtue and accomplishments may be inscribed in history and grace your family records, that your household may shine and your court grow luminous with worthy visitors. All gifts and properties detailed in the separate record are hereby granted to you. Receive them with our favor. As winter's chill descends, etc.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mao tu (茅土): The ancient fief granted to meritorious officials, symbolized by a bundle of grass and a portion of earth.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yellow River shall become a belt, Tai Mountain a whetstone: A classical Chinese expression meaning ''even if these eternal things change, I shall not forget.'''
  - key: ''
    value: 'Three Lands (三韓): A reference to the Korean peninsula and its territories.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jinyang (晋陽): An important historical region, here used as the marquis title.'
  - key: ''
    value: This appears to be an official royal edict, possibly from the Goryeo period, addressed to a high-ranking official or general upon his elevation in rank.
